Comment: To be honest this mix of time periods actually is pretty nice imo bc it immerses you in a mixture of fantasy and reality. The mix of time periods gives you those fantasy world vibes but the mention of historical events/actual places ties it to reality and in a certain way it matches Robin Hood because he actually existed, he is a real person, but his story is surrounded by legends so much that in a certain way, he has become a myth. His story sounds so much like a legend that ppl often forget he really existed. So yeah the mix between fantasy and reality in the setting matches the character so I found it a pretty good move on the producers part.

Title: Robin Hood (2018 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì Taron Egerton, Jamie Foxx, Jamie Dornan
Comment:
Unpopular opinion: This movie was great. 

I love that the fashion style is more relaxed and that the characters look real and believable. Marian for example never has super extravagant hair or clothes. Sure she wears darker eyeshadow, but it suits her character and shows that she has a bit of a darker, wild side. It makes her more relatable.

I enjoyed the friendship between John and Robin, along with watching them train as well. Going from, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm trying to kill you,‚Äù to ‚ÄúI will die for you.‚Äù Those have always been my favorite types of relationships, platonic or otherwise.

Speaking of relationships, I absolutely love the way Robin met Marian. It was so different from other retellings, and again, showed another side to her character. I really just loved their entire relationship. It was sad, watching Robin literally get sick after he saw Marian with Will, but it made his character stronger. Marian became his drive and I find that absolutely sweet.

Now to the action. I was literally on the edge of my seat every time there was a robbery scene. Robin‚Äôs badassery with a bow is just amazing. Being someone who enjoys doing archery very much, I found it absolutely incredible! The only time I ever got upset was when Robin‚Äôs face was showing, like ‚ÄúPull the scarf up for the love of God! This is a heist!‚Äù

The war scenes toward the beginning of the film were so great and I can‚Äôt stress how much I love the fact that Robin was seeing flashbacks at the end of the film, when the people from the mines were fighting the soldiers. That just showed how much he cared for his people and that he was willing to sacrifice everything, including his life for them. Btw, John helping him escape and kill the sheriff? Completely a badass dynamic duo moment.

This film set up for a sequel and I really hope they make one. Robin, finally, fully accepted his role as a thief. I want to see more! This was an origin story and I‚Äôm ready for the next piece. 

‚ÄúWelcome to the big table, Sheriff.‚Äù

I. Want. A. Sequel.

Title: Robin Hood (2018 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì Taron Egerton, Jamie Foxx, Jamie Dornan
Comment:
I've seen it. It's as bad as you think.

-Action is cut like a Marvel movie
-Robin has his damn mask off half the time he's in battle and somehow his identity isn't given away
-Yes, Marion is actually wearing that outfit in the movie.
-Molotov cocktails in the era of Robin Hood where he fights in the Crusades. That happened
-The comic relief friar character (Tillman was it?) is utterly lame
-Robin gets an arrow TO THE HEART in the climax, Marion pulls it out, and he lives WITHOUT MEDICAL ATTENTION
-Whoever directed this film thinks that a small trail of flammable fluid on the ground creates a huge inferno
-John just "apparates" where the movie needs him to be. He's somehow on the boat back to England in the opening, then he's somehow masquerading as the Sheriff's guard in the climax (the last time we saw John before that scene, he'd found the room in the prison where the guards kept their armor. We don't even see how he made his way into the guard. We don't even know how he knew that Robin had willingly let himself be captured so that the Sheriff could have him executed. He's just...THERE)
-Apparently the townsfolk call him "The Hood" because the director thinks that 13th century Englishmen have cool nicknames for noble people like him.
-Nobody even attempts to talk Middle English.
-There's basically a Canto Bight scene in the middle of the movie where they're gambling on 13th century roulette wheels and throwing weird-shaped dice and it honestly looks like some extravagant Vegas party.
-For literally no reason, John forbids Robin from talking to Marion at the start of the movie...which gets forgotten within 15 minutes because after that point, Robin and Marion are having regular conversations and John doesn't give a shit.

The completely-not-subtle relation to Antifa doesn't even need to be mentioned. The rest of the film's bad enough.

Title: Robin Hood (2018 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì Taron Egerton, Jamie Foxx, Jamie Dornan
Comment: In my opinion cast of Robin Hood it's an unfortunate one. The English colonial project only really gets going in the middle of the 17th century. Black people came to England through English trade with Africa; from southern Europe, where there were black (slave) populations in Spain and Portugal. The legend of Robin Hood came to life in the second half of the 15th century, so, black people were insignificant or none! Also, hair style! As I looked at more 15th century paintings, I could see that men in general seemed to have longish hair and clean-shaven faces back then. Later on in the 16th century, men cut their hair short and grew beards. No one had a clean shave head on that time, unless you were a slave or a prisoner.

Title: Robin Hood (2018 Movie) Official Trailer ‚Äì Taron Egerton, Jamie Foxx, Jamie Dornan
Comment:
This looks awful. They changed out so many elements of the core Robin Hood stories that they may as well have made an entirely new story & setting. Doesn't help that the clothes everyone wears look like Old Navy castoffs. The Sheriff looks like Grand Moff Tarkin, the city looks like it belongs in the Italian Renaissance, and if you wanted a diverse cast for a film set in Europe during the age of bows & swords then I can point to any number of vibrant port cities in the Mediterranean which would fit the bill better than "Nottingham."  

Even worse it looks like four movies rolled into one cheesy premise. We have a vigilante hero story, a class warfare story, a casino heist film and then we have a guy called Robin Hood with a Bow who wants to steal. I get that Hollywood wants to play it safe and use an established premise rather than creating their own story, but isn't it more dangerous to put out B rated films that are almost certain to bomb?
